We have seen that each of $-\otimes_R M$, $\operatorname{Hom}_R(M,-)$, and $\operatorname{Hom}_R(-,M)$ is an additive functor. Left exactness of   $\operatorname{Hom}_R(M,-)$ . This is almost tautological from the universal property of kernels. For a morphism $\phi : M 	o N$, we know that \(0 	o \operatorname{Hom}_R(T,\ker \phi) 	o \operatorname{Hom}_R(T,M) 	o \operatorname{Hom}_R(T,N)\) is exact. In other words, we preserve kernels: \(\operatorname{Hom}_R(T,\ker \phi) \cong \ker \left( \operatorname{Hom}_R(T,M) 	o \operatorname{Hom}_R(T,N) ight)\) . The same argument in a general abelian category shows that $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal A}(A,-)$ is left exact. Left exactness (in the opposite category) of   $\operatorname{Hom}_R(-,M)$ . In the other entry, we get a functor $\left( \operatorname{Mod} R ight)^{op} 	o \operatorname{Ab}$. The opposite category $\left( \operatorname{Mod} R ight)^{op}$ has the structure of abelian category where we exchange kernels and cokernels. From the universal property of cokernels we know that \(\operatorname{Hom}_R(\operatorname{coker} \phi, T) \cong \ker \left( \operatorname{Hom}_R(N,T) 	o \operatorname{Hom}_R(M,T) ight)\) Reversing the arrows, we see that $\operatorname{Hom}_R(-,M)$ takes the kernels in $\left( \operatorname{Mod} R ight)^{op}$ to kernels. Again, the same argument works in a general abelian category. Right exactness of   $- \otimes_R M$ . Assume we have an exact sequence \(M \overset{\mu}{	o} N \overset{
u}{	o} C 	o 0\) in $\operatorname{Mod} R$. Then $C \cong M/N$. If we apply $- \otimes_R T$ we get \(M \otimes_R T \overset{\mu \otimes 1}{	o} N \otimes_R T \overset{
u \otimes 1}{	o} C \otimes_R T 	o 0\) and we want to check exactness. We need to first check that each element of $C \otimes_R T$ is in the image of $N \otimes_R T$. Pick some element $\sum c_i \otimes t_i$. Since $N 	o C$ is surjective, we can find $n_i$ with $n_i \mapsto c_i$ for each $i$. Then \(\sum n_i \otimes t_i \mapsto \sum c_i \otimes t_i.\) . Assume we can construct a map $\lambda: C \otimes_R T 	o (M \otimes_R T)/(N \otimes_R T)$ making the diagram . where the arrows labelled with $=$ are the identity maps. Assume that we have some element $ x \in N \otimes_R T$ with $(
u \otimes 1)(x) = 0$. Then, we also know that $\pi(x) = 0$. So there exists a $y \in M \otimes_R T$ with $(\mu \otimes 1)(y) = x$ giving exactness at $N \otimes_R T$. Now we turn to making $\lambda$ using the universal property of tensor products. Consider \( egin{aligned} C 	imes T &amp; 	o (N \otimes_R T)/(M \otimes_R T) \ (c,t) &amp; \mapsto \overline{	ilde{c} \otimes t} \end{aligned}\) where $	ilde{c}$ is a choice of element of $N$ such that $
u(	ilde{c}) = c$. We need to check this is well-defined and $R$-bilinear. Any other lift of $c$ is of the form $	ilde{c} + n$ for some $n \in N$. We have \(\overline{(	ilde{c} + n) \otimes t} = \overline{	ilde{c} \otimes t + n \otimes t} = \overline{	ilde{c} \otimes t}.\) Thus the function is well-defined. Since $	ilde{c}r$ is a lift of $cr$, we see that we have an $R$-bilinear function. Thus, we get a unique $\lambda : C \otimes_R T 	o (N \otimes_R T)/(M \otimes_R T)$ with \(\lambda(c \otimes t) = \overline{	ilde{c} \otimes t}\) This gives us the desired diagram and finishes the argument. Non-exactness . Consider $k[x]$ for $k$ a field. And write $k = k[x]/(x)$. We have an exact sequence \(0 	o k[x] \overset{x}{	o} k[x] 	o k 	o 0\) If we apply $\operatorname{Hom}_{k[x]}(k,-)$ this turns into \(0 	o 0 	o 0 	o k 	o 0\) which is not exact at $k$. Hence $\operatorname{Hom}_R(M,-)$ is not right exact in general. If we apply $- \otimes_{k[x]} k$ to our exact sequence instead we get \(0 	o k \overset{0}{	o} k 	o k 	o 0\) which show that $- \otimes_R M$ is not left exact in general. Similarly, if we apply $\operatorname{Hom}_{k[x]}(-,k)$, we get \(0 \leftarrow k \overset{0}{\leftarrow} k \leftarrow k \leftarrow 0\) which shows that $\operatorname{Hom}_R(-,M)$ is not right exact in general.
